<i>reveler</i> ‘to revel’). Alternatively, the name may also arise from the Middle English personal name <i>Revel</i>, itself from the adjective above."],"variants":[{"name":"Revelle","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Revell  . This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Revill","meanings":["English: variant of   Revell  ."]},{"name":"Reville","meanings":["English and Irish: variant of   Revell  , especially in Ireland.","French: habitational name from any of the three places called Reville, in Manche, Meuse, and Loiret."]},{"name":"Revel","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Gaston, Henri, Pascal.","French: habitational name from any of the places so named, for example in Isère and Haute-Garonne.","French: nickname from Old French, Occitan <i>reveau</i> ‘rebel’."]},{"name":"Revels","meanings":["English (Cumberland and Yorkshire): variant of   Revell  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>.","Scottish: habitational name from Raffles in Mouswald (Dumfriesshire), comprising Old Norse <i>ref-hol</i> ‘fox-hole’ in a Scots plural form."]},{"name":"Reveal","meanings":["Probably an altered form of English   Revell  ."]}]},{"name":"Hugh","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Hugues</i>, <i>Hugo</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>hug</i> ‘heart, mind, spirit’. It was originally a short form of various compound names containing this element. This was borne by the aristocracy of medieval France, adopted by the Normans, and introduced by them to Britain. It was consistently one of the most popular boys' names in the Middle Ages in England, but fell out of favour in the 16th century until it was revived in the 20th century. Little Hugh of Lincoln was a child supposed in the Middle Ages to have been murdered by Jews in about  1255 , a legend responsible for several outbursts of anti-Semitism at various times. The story is referred to by  Chaucer  in The Prioress's Tale. He is not to be confused with  St Hugh of Lincoln  (  1140–1200 ), bishop of Lincoln (  1186–1200 ), who was noted for his charity and good works, his piety, and his defence of the Church against the State. Since the later Middle Ages <i>Hugh</i> has also been used as an Anglicized form of the Gaelic name Aodh ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705192,"age":10,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":19,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705195,"age":64,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Hugh Revell was born in 1318, in Maidstone, Kent, England, his father, Robert Revelle, was 18 and his mother, Mrs. Robert Revelle, was 19. He married Alice De Wappenbury in 1338, in Maidstone, Kent, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1416, in his hometown, at the age of 98."},"et":{"1318–1416":"1318–1416","1318–1399":"1318–1399","1340–1399":"1340–1399","1300–Male":"1300–Surnud","1299–Female":"1299–Surnud","1340":"1340","JAN 1399":"jaanuar 1399","1382":"13